<F P=100> Philippines </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ramos Meets Australian Foreign Minister </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ramos Meets Australian Foreign Minister </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1406055394 Quezon City Radio Filipinas in English 0230 GMT 
14 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1406055394 </F>
<F P=104>  Quezon City Radio Filipinas </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] President Fidel V. Ramos and visiting Australian 
Foreign Minister Gareth Evans agreed on Monday to further 
strengthen the existing harmonious relations between their 
respective countries [word indistinct] trade and investment. 
The president and Minister Evans made the commitment during 
their 30-minute meeting in Malacanang [presidential office], 
which was also attended by Foreign Affairs Secretary Roberto 
Romulo, Presidential Assistant for Mindanao Paul Dominguez and 
Australian Ambassador Richard Smith. 
  Minister Evans assured the president of the Australian 
Government's continuing support to his administration as well as 
his personal commitment to help the Philippines obtain progress 
and development. Australia is the third largest economy in Asia 
and the 14th in the world, with 60 percent of its exports now 
going to the East Asian region. Minister Evans told the 
president he visited several investment centers including Subic 
Bay Free Port in Zambales and Davao City and General Santos City 
in Mindanao. Minister Evans visited Mindanao last 10 to 11 June 
with members of his official delegation to explore possibilities 
of linking Australia's northern territory with Mindanao. He 
informed the president of Australia's keen interest in the East 
ASEAN Growth Area or EAGA concept of economically grouping 
Brunei Darussalam, Indonesia, Malaysia and the Philippines. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-28753 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas114_l_94003" </HT>


