Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Philippines </F>
<H3> <TI>   Abu Sayyaf Group Releases 20 of 21 Hostages </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Abu Sayyaf Group Releases 20 of 21 Hostages </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1406055194 Quezon City Radio Filipinas in English 0230 GMT 
14 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1406055194 </F>
<F P=104>  Quezon City Radio Filipinas </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Twenty out of the 21 Christian hostages have been 
finally released after being taken captive by the Abu Sayyaf 
group in Basilan for six days. The only remaining hostage is 
Father Cirilo Lacorda. The announcement was made by Armed 
Forces Chief General Arturo Enrile in a news conference last 
night at a military camp in Manila after receiving the report 
from Armed Forces Southern Command Chief Orlando Soriano. Based 
on the report, all the hostages, including 18 public school 
teachers, were freed Monday afternoon. Enrile said that the 
release of 20 Christian hostages was made possible with the 
intervention of the civilian negotiators led by Basilan Governor 
Gerry Salabudin to the local Abu Sayyaf leader Barhama Sali 
alias Amir. However, the AFP [Armed Forces of the Philippines] 
Chief of Staff did not mention whether the demand of the 
kidnappers for a P[Philippine pesos] 1 million ransom for the 
safe release of the hostages was paid. There are reports that 
Gov. Salabudin paid P200,000.00 for the release of the 20 
hostages. 
  Earlier, government authorities met three of the five 
demands 
sought by the notorious group of Muslim-based bandits for the 
safe release of the hostages. Among these demands include: the 
reinstatement of 737 Basilan-based schoolteachers who were 
earlier terminated form service because they were not Civil 
Service eligibles; disallowing the wearing of short pants by 
female Muslim students during physical education activities and 
allowing them to wear turbans while inside the campus and not to 
allow military and police authorities to interfere with the 
ongoing negotiations between the government and the bandits led 
by (Juljilang). 
  The Abu Sayyaf group is also demanding the suspension of 
military and police offensives in Basilan. However, AFP Chief 
Arturo Enrile said that despite the safe release of the 
hostages, massive military operations will resume against the 
dreaded extreme Muslim fundamentalists operating in the 
Provinces of Sulu, Basilan, Maguindanao, Cotabato and in the 
cities of Zamboanga, Davao, Cotabato and General Santos. 
General Enrile deployed a battalion of marine contingents from 
Luzon to provide reinforcement to the government forces in 
Mindanao. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-28755 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas114_l_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-114 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Philippines </F>
<H3> <TI>   Military Support for Abu Sayyaf Group Suspected </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Military Support for Abu Sayyaf Group Suspected </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1306144894 Quezon City GMA-7 Radio-Television Arts Network 
in Tagalog 0930 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1306144894 </F>
<F P=104>  Quezon City GMA-7 Radio-Television Arts Network 
in Tagalog 0930 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Tagalog </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Senator Santanina Rasul suspects the terrorist Abu 
Sayyaf group is being supported by the military. According to 
Rasul, several persons have told her they saw the military 
helping some active members of the Abu Sayyaf group. 
  [Begin Rasul recording in English] There are those who feel 
that the Abu Sayyaf or some people in the Abu Sayyaf are 
supported by the military. And I think the military should look 
into this angle -- that one of the leaders was seen being 
ferried by a PCF [expansion unknown], being ferried by a 
military chief, and escorted by military personnel in Basilan. 
  So again, this has given rise to suspicion that maybe the 
Abu 
Sayyaf are not really what they are. Maybe, it is something 
more that, [pause] more than meets the eye. But on my part, as 
a leader of this region -- as a Muslim leader -- I feel that 
this incident should not be used to project the idea of 
Muslim-Christian conflict. [end recording] 
  This statement followed information released by Criminal 
Investigation Service Regional Command 9, which stated that the 
firearms confiscated from Mujin Aminudin who is allegedly the 
supply officer of Abu Sayyaf, came from the Logistics Command of 
the Armed Forces of the Philippines at Camp Aguinaldo. 
  Senator Rasul also said that the root cause of the Abu 
Sayyaf 
problem is attributed to the slow pace of the government's peace 
talks with the Muslim rebels, as well as the military's failure 
to grant Abu Sayyaf's earlier requests on their previous 
kidnapping operations. 
  [Begin Rasul recording in English] So, I think we have to 
fast track this peace process with the Moro National Liberation 
Front [MNLF]. Otherwise, we will find ourselves on the losing 
end. The people who should be supporting the government might 
be incited by this extremist group to join forces with them 
because they feel that nothing much is happening in the peace 
talks between the MNLF and the government. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

