<H3> <TI>   More on Issues Related to Bilateral Trade Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    More on Issues Related to Bilateral Trade Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    MITI on Repeal of Semiconductor Accord </H4>

<F P=102> OW1406060994 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 14 
Jun 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1406060994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 14 June Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] A senior official of the Ministry of International 
Trade and Industry [MITI] disclosed on 13 June a plan to submit 
a proposal at Japan-U.S. semiconductor talks due to be held in 
Tokyo on 15 June to abolish the Japan-U.S. semiconductor accord. 
  The official said: "The effects of abolishing the 
semiconductor accord will considered beneficial." Both 
countries are supposed to decided by the end of July whether or 
not the accord should be retained. 
  The official added: "The accord sets a bad example, and 
gives the United States an excuse to impose sanctions against 
Japan." 
  It seems, though, the Tokyo meeting faces heavy weather 
because the United States sees the accord as an example of a 
successful agreement between Japan and the United States. 
  The main purpose of the Tokyo meeting is to see if progress 
has been made in allowing foreign companies make inroads into 
Japanese markets. Prior to government-level discussions, a 
meeting of specialists began on 13 June to calculate the 
semiconductor market share enjoyed by foreign companies in the 
February-March period in 1994. 
  Japan has decided to look at the possibility of abolishing 
the semiconductor accord because it believes the United States 
should not "threaten us by hinting at the possibility of 
imposing sanctions on the grounds of market share." 

</TEXT>

