<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reform Council Recommends Further Deregulation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reform Council Recommends Further Deregulation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0806003094 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 6 Jun 94 
Evening Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0806003094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On 6 June, expert members of the working group on 
"Import Promotion, Market Access Improvement, and Distribution" 
of the government's Administrative Reform Promotion 
Council(headed by Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata), presented a 
report recommending abolition or alleviation of Japan's unique 
regulations as well as drastic reduction of gaps in commodity 
prices between Japan and other countries to the cabinet minister 
in charge of the group. 
  This means all three working groups under the council have 
presented their reports. On deregulation of some individual 
regulations, however, this last report presented dual 
alternatives, leaving the government to make decisions on what 
alternatives to choose. 
  The report was prepared by compiling the views of seven 
expert members representing academic and economic circles, and 
it recommends, among others: 1) Abolishing or easing Japan's 
unique economic regulations; 2) adopting as a target the 
reduction of gaps in commodity prices between Japan and other 
countries by half; 3) abolishing or easing rules which impede 
business operations; and 4) establishing without delay an 
administrative reform committee without any present or former 
bureaucrats represented on it. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

