<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   ASEAN Members Urged To Speed Up AFTA Cuts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ASEAN Members Urged To Speed Up AFTA Cuts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1106111594 Bangkok BANGKOK POST in English 11 Jun 94 p 15 </F>
<F P=103> BK1106111594 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok BANGKOK POST </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] ASEAN Free Trade Area [AFTA] members should speed up 
the reduction of taxes to below 5 percent on products that have 
potential to attract foreign investment in the region, according 
to Suwan Phasuksawat, deputy director-general of the Fiscal 
Policy Office. 
  While AFTA participants have agreed to reduce taxes on many 
products to between zero and 5 percent within periods ranging 
from eight to 15 years, the reductions should be expedited in 
some cases, he said. 
  Mr Suwan headed the Thai delegation at the ASEAN senior 
officials' meeting in Indonesia on June 3 and 4. Besides 
discussing tariff cuts, participants also reviewed measures that 
are considered non-tariff barriers under the framework of the 
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. 
  Under the AFTA framework, non-tariff barriers will have to 
be 
scrapped within the next five years. 

</TEXT>

