Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   MP's Urged To Unite To Forge New Constitution </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    MP's Urged To Unite To Forge New Constitution </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1106103494 Bangkok THE NATION in English 11 Jun 94 pp A1, 
A4 </F>

<F P=103> BK1106103494 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok THE NATION </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] More than 100 leading academics yesterday made 
public an open letter demanding the government and the 
opposition jointly set up a special committee to draft a new, 
more democratic constitution. 
  One hundred and thirteen intellectuals from institutions 
across the country -- including Chulalongkon, Chiang Mai, 
Songkhla Nakharin, Khon Kaen, Mahidon and Thammasat universities 
-- signed their names to the letter. 
  Organizers said it would be submitted to House Speaker Marut 
Bunnak on Monday. 
  The letter said all politicians should cooperate to resolve 
the political impasse fuelled by activist Chalat Worachat's 
hunger strike as soon as possible, before a national crisis 
develops. 
  The academics accused the Democrat Party of being insincere 
in its effort to ease the current political tensions. 
  Efforts to end Chalat's hunger strike should not be used as 
a 
bargaining chip by any political group seeking to take advantage 
of the situation. 
  All politicians, and in particular government MPs, should be 
decisive in resolving the impasse, the letter said. Opposition 
MPs had already declared their full support for Chalat's demand 
for a House committee to draft a new charter. 
  Surichai Wankaeo, deputy dean of Chulalongkon University's 
Political Science Faculty, said the letter was aimed at 
prompting the government to introduce more democratic changes. 
  He said if democracy was enhanced Chalat may decide to quit 
his hunger strike. 
  Academic Suchai Trirat said the people should not consider 
Chalat's hunger strike "pressure outside Parliament" as Chalat's 
purpose was to help develop the parliamentary system. 
  "Politics does not mean only the people inside Parliament," 
he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

