<F P=100> AUSTRALASIA </F>
<F P=101> Papua New Guinea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Paints `Gloomy' Picutre of Economy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister Paints `Gloomy' Picutre of Economy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1406064594 Melbourne Radio Australia in English 0500 GMT 
14 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1406064594 </F>
<F P=104>  Melbourne Radio Australia </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Papua New Guinea's [PNG] minister for finance and 
planning, Masket Iangalio, has painted a gloomy picture of the 
country's economy and says government revenue is well below 
expectations. 
  In an interview with the Port Moresby newspaper, THE 
NATIONAL, Mr. Iangalio said that although export prices for oil 
and other commodities were rising and PNG was experiencing a 
high level of economic growth, the government budget deficit was 
unacceptably high, and foreign reserves were falling to crisis 
level. He blamed Papua New Guinea's financial troubles in part 
on the closure of the Bougainville copper mine, over optimistic 
estimates of government income and success of budget, and 
uncontrolled spending by the public sector over a number of 
years. 

</TEXT>

