<H3> <TI>   Tokyo's Reaction to DPRK's Withdrawal from IAEA </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tokyo's Reaction to DPRK's Withdrawal from IAEA </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Possible Sanctions Considered </H4>

<F P=102> OW1406045694 Tokyo NHK General Television Network in 
Japanese 0300 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1406045694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NHK General Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The government disclosed at the House of 
Councillors' Budget Committee today that it is studying concrete 
measures to be taken if economic sanctions are imposed against 
North Korea, including a halt on remittances, and restrictions 
on exports and imports. 
  According to Justice Minister Hiroshi Nakai, Finance 
Minister 
Hirohisa Fujii, Minister of International Trade and Industry 
Eijiro Hata, and Transport Minister Nobuaki Futami, specific 
measures being considered include: A ban on North Korean 
diplomats' entry into Japan, a halt to remittances under the 
Foreign Exchange Control Act, restrictions on exports and 
imports and the services trade under the Export and Import Trade 
Control Order, surveillance of ships by the Maritime Safety 
Agency following amendment of the Trade Control Order. The 
ministers disclosed that the concerned government ministries and 
agencies were studying concrete steps to restrict personnel 
traffic and exports and imports. 

</TEXT>

