<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Official Denies Developing Nuclear Weapons </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK Official Denies Developing Nuclear Weapons </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1406030294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0250 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1406030294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 14 KYODO -- North Korea told a 
delegation from Japan's Social Democratic Party [of Japan] (SDP) 
[SDPJ] that the country is not trying to develop nuclear 
weapons, SDPJ officials said Tuesday. 
  Hwang Chang-yop, the Korean Worker's Party's secretary in 
charge of international affairs, told the visiting delegation of 
SDPJ legislators in Pyongyang that "North Korea will not have 
nuclear bombs" and has neither the technology nor funds for such 
a purpose. 
  SDPJ officials in Tokyo said the legislators headed by House 
of Representatives member Kazo Watanabe held talks with North 
Korean officials in Pyongyang on Monday. 
  Watanabe reportedly conveyed a message from Prime Minister 
Tsutomu Hata to the effect that resolution of the nuclear row 
through dialogue will help improve relations between Japan and 
North Korea. The two countries have no diplomatic relations. 
  Hwang's remarks echo comments by North Korean President Kim 
Il-song in the fall of 1990 to a joint delegation of the Liberal 
Democratic Party (LDP) and SDPJ members. 
  The SDPJ delegation entered the North Korean capital via 
Beijing on Saturday and held talks with ruling party officials, 
including Kim Yong-sun, chairman of the reunification policy 
committee, over the nuclear problems and bilateral issues. 
  The delegation is returning home Tuesday by way of Beijing. 
  The SDPJ, Japan's second largest opposition party, has 
traditionally maintained close relations with North Korea, which 
is suspected of pursuing a nuclear weapons development program. 

</TEXT>

