<H3> <TI>   Mitsui To Conduct LPG Feasibility Study in SRV </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mitsui To Conduct LPG Feasibility Study in SRV </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1006025594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0243 GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1006025594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 10 KYODO -- Mitsui and Co., Japan's 
giant trading house, will look into the possibility of a 400 
million dollar liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) project in Vietnam 
in conjunction with three foreign partners, a Mitsui official 
said Friday [10 June]. 
  The three other parties involved are Vietnam's public oil 
company PetroVietnam, British Gas PLC and TransCanada Pipelines 
Ltd., the official said. 
  Depending on the result of a feasibility study to be 
conducted soon, the parties involved in the project will set up 
a joint concern as early as this year to explore natural gas 
flowing out of an oil field off the southern Vietnamese coast. 
  The project calls for laying a 130-kilometer pipeline 
linking 
the oil field with an LPG plant in Vung Tau, southeast of Ho Chi 
Minh City. 
  Production is slated to begin in the latter half of 1996 at 
the earliest, with annual production of some 260,000 tons 
intended for export to Japan, China and Southeast Asia as well 
as for use at local power plants, the official added. 

</TEXT>

