<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo, EU To Sign Pact on Business Cooperation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tokyo, EU To Sign Pact on Business Cooperation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1406101994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1007 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1406101994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 14 KYODO -- Japan and the European 
Union (EU) on Tuesday [14 June] agreed to cooperate further in 
enhancing each other's industrial foundation, Japanese Trade 
Ministry officials said. 
  At the end of the second "Japan-EU Industrial Policy and 
Cooperation Dialogue" in Tokyo, Japan's Ministry of 
International Trade and Industry (MITI) and the European 
Commission issued a joint statement calling for industrial 
cooperation not only in existing areas such as electric home 
appliances but in new sectors like computers, auto parts and 
office equipment, the officials said. 
  The statement said both parties will also support dialogue 
between Japanese and EU business leaders to be held by the end 
of this year under the newly established "roundtable." Under 
the manufacturing technology fellowship program, young European 
engineers will be invited to work in Japanese plants for up to 
one year, the statement said. 
  The MITI officials said Japan and the EU confirmed the 
importance of further action in existing cooperative areas, 
among them the training of European engineers through the 
Industrial Cooperation Center (ICC). The ICC was created in 
Tokyo in 1987 as a way to get European companies accustomed to 
Japanese business practices and market conditions. 
  Sozaburo Okamatsu, vice MITI minister for international 
affairs, led a Japanese team at Tuesday's meeting while the 
European side was headed by Riccardo Perissich, chief of the 
European Commission's Industry Bureau [name and title as 
received]. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

