<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata Plans End to Fray Over War Guilt </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata Plans End to Fray Over War Guilt </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0906143594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1427 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0906143594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 9 KYODO -- Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata 
plans to offer an explicit apology to nations victimized by 
Japan's war conduct next year when Japan commemorates the 50th 
anniversary of its surrender in World War II, a top government 
official said. 
  "Prime Minister Hata is considering putting an end to a fray 
to alleviate all the troubles (surrounding Japan's war 
reparation) by taking the opportunity on the 50th anniversary of 
the end of World War II," the official said on condition of 
anonymity. 
  Hata plans to resolve controversies involving redress for 
former "comfort women," who were forced into prostitution by 
Japan's Imperial Army before and during World War II, and 
Japan's confiscation of postal savings of Taiwanese citizens 
then under Japanese rule, he said. 
  Unpaid money that includes the postal savings deposited by 
Taiwanese before and during World War II total 452.4 million 
yen, according to a government estimate. 
  In a related development, Hata became the first Japanese 
prime minister to meet with Korean and Philippine comfort women 
Thursday [9 June]. The unofficial meeting was arranged in a 
Diet corridor. 
  Hata also wants to arrange for a Diet resolution that Japan 
will not invade other countries again and for various official 
projects and ceremonies commemorating the 50th anniversary, he 
said. 
  However, Japan remains reluctant to make any individual 
reparation payments or to take "actions that could be a 
substitute for the reparation," the official said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

