<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 14 KYODO -- Shoichiro Toyoda, chairman 
of the Federation of Economic Organizations (Keidanren), called 
Tuesday [14 Jun] on Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata for his 
cabinet's leadership in implementing deregulation and other 
administrative reform, officials said. 
  "The cabinet should break the wall of vested interests and 
lead administrative reforms decisively," Toyoda told Hata in a 
meeting at the prime minister's official residence. 
  Toyoda and Keidanren's Vice Chairman Isao Nakauchi asked 
Hata 
to set a target to halve the number of economic regulations in 
five years. 
  He also called on Hata to map out a plan for scrapping and 
privatizing government-backed corporations. 
  Hata responded that the reforms and deregulations are a 
national problem which must be tackled. 
  At the day's cabinet meeting, Hata instructed ministers to 
display leadership in their ministries and agencies in compiling 
deregulation measures by the end of the month. 

</TEXT>

