<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 13 KYODO -- The head of the powerful 
Federation of Economic Organizations (Keidanren) expressed 
support Monday [13 June] for the planned abolition of a 
provisional law regulating imports of oil products. 
  It is natural to abolish the law in line with economic 
deregulation, Shoichiro Toyoda, chairman of the elite business 
club, told a news conference, referring to a plan by the Trade 
Ministry to abolish the law. 
  He said deregulation is a major task to be tackled and 
should 
be pushed ahead by all means. 
  Toyoda, who is chairman of Japan's top automaker Toyota 
Motor 
Corp., said he was not confident enough on an economic recovery 
although there were some bright signs. 
  He said the present value of the Japanese yen is too high in 
view of Japan's fundamental economic conditions and it should be 
brought down to an optimum level, or around 110 yen to the 
dollar. 

</TEXT>

