<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Standards for Public Works Bidders To Be Set </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Standards for Public Works Bidders To Be Set </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1306075894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0744 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1306075894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 13 KYODO -- The Construction Ministry 
will introduce a system to consider technical standards, as well 
as the bidding price, in choosing successful bidders for public 
works contracts, ministry officials said Monday [13 June]. 
  They said the new system is to apply on an experimental 
basis 
to ministry-controlled public works projects, beginning fiscal 
1994, which started April 1. 
  The present system, which awards a public works contract to 
the lowest bidder, contributes to bid rigging and unfair price 
competition, critics say. 
  The new system gives overall numerical ratings to bidders, 
including noise and vibration control measures and designing, in 
addition to the bidding price, the officials said. 
  The government had earlier used a bid evaluation system 
based 
on technical standards and cost in choosing successful bidders 
for supercomputer supply contracts. 

</TEXT>

