<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   MITI Urges Improvement of `Techno-Infrastructure' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    MITI Urges Improvement of `Techno-Infrastructure' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1406093494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0916 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1406093494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 14 KYODO -- The Ministry of 
International Trade and Industry (MITI) on Tuesday [14 June] 
underscored the importance of Japan beefing up its 
"techno-infrastructure" in a guideline for research and 
development of industrial and scientific technology. 
  The government should "drastically" expand budgetary 
appropriations for reinforcing Japan's overall technological 
foundation in line with the guideline, a MITI official told a 
press conference. The official said the level of a country's 
techno- infrastructure can be enhanced by improvements in 
various factors, such as human resources, information, facility 
construction, fund raising, protection of intellectual property 
rights and the deregulation of research activity. 
  Japan's technological standards should be raised through 
active research activity, not only by specialized organs like 
MITI institutes but also by private-sector research entities, 
the official said. The public sector should devote itself to 
improving the general research environment for private organs 
and universities, the official said. 
  The guideline cited nine major industrial and scientific 
sectors as areas of priority study. Among them are new 
materials, biotechnology, space technology, medical equipment, 
clean energy development, new resources and information and 
communications. 

</TEXT>

