<H3> <TI>   Hata Urges Lower Domestic Prices </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata Urges Lower Domestic Prices </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1306042694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0358 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1306042694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 13 KYODO -- Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata 
called for lower domestic prices Monday [13 Jun], saying the gap 
between prices in Japan and overseas should be narrowed. 
  "To make our lives richer, we have to directly address the 
issue of rectifying the gap between domestic and overseas 
prices," he told a private advisory panel, urging it to come up 
with specific recommendations for that purpose. 
  It is the 13th meeting for the panel, an advisory body on 
prices to the prime minister. 
  The panel has 44 members, including economic experts and 
people in the industrial, labor, and consumer fields chosen to 
give their opinions on bringing down Japan's prices to 
international levels. 
  Sources close to the panel say it remains to be seen what 
specific measures it will be able to recommend, since policies 
so far have been unable to tug domestic prices lower despite the 
appreciation of the yen. 
  The panel is likely to base its discussions on a report 
compiled by a research committee that was set up last fall. 
  Economic Planning Agency Director General Yoshio Terasawa 
and 
other cabinet members also attended the meeting. 

</TEXT>

