<H3> <TI>   Interest Rates on Housing Loans To Be Liberalized </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Interest Rates on Housing Loans To Be Liberalized </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1306115594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1112 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1306115594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 13 KYODO -- The Finance Ministry plans 
to liberalize interest rates on housing loans charged by 
commercial banks in July at the earliest, ministry sources said 
Monday [13 June]. 
  The sources said the decontrol will be incorporated in an 
economic deregulation package to be worked out by the government 
at the end of June. 
  They said banks would be accused of violating the 
antimonopoly law if they manipulate interest rates on housing 
loans through behind-the-scenes negotiations. 
  Fixed and variable interest rates on housing loans, 
introduced in 1983, have been linked to movements of the 
long-term prime lending rate charged by commercial banks on 
loans to creditworthy customers. 
  The sources said commercial banks are studying the 
possibility of linking housing loan interest with the short-term 
prime rate, which reflects interest movements on the money 
market. 

</TEXT>

