<H3> <TI>   Robust Exports Restore Kyushu Microchip Industry </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Robust Exports Restore Kyushu Microchip Industry </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1106065294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0634 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1106065294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Fukuoka, June 11 KYODO -- The computer microchip 
industry in Kyushu, known as Japan's Silicon Valley, is 
regaining vitality on the strength of brisk exports, Trade 
Ministry officials said Saturday [11 June]. 
  According to the Kyushu Regional Bureau of International 
Trade and Industry, total production of integrated circuits 
(ICs) in the Kyushu region in April hit a record high of about 
670.6 million chips. 
  April marked the 15th consecutive month of year-to-year 
rises, said the regional bureau of the Ministry of International 
Trade and Industry (MITI). 
  An official of major microchip manufacturer Oki Electric 
Industry Co.'s semiconductor factory in Miyazaki Prefecture said 
the record- breaking output reflects "strong exports to the 
United States due to robust demand for personal computers there." 
  "A great number of microchip makers are building new 
facilities to boost production capacities," he said. 
  In 1992, ic output in Kyushu plunged 11 percent from the 
year 
before to 6.36 billion chips. 
  Production began to show signs of picking up early this 
year. 
In February, the first year-on-year rise in about two years was 
seen. 
  IC production surged to 668,637,000 chips the following 
month, the highest level since the 670 million scored in 
September 1993. 

</TEXT>

