<H3> <TI>   Government Efforts on Economic Recovery Urged </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Efforts on Economic Recovery Urged </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1306043194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0318 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1306043194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 13 KYODO -- The Federation of Economic 
Organizations (Keidanren) on Monday [13 Jun] called for the 
government to take all kinds of measures to put the Japanese 
economy on a steady recovery track, a trade ministry official 
said. 
  Chairman Shoichiro Toyoda and other senior Keidanren 
executives made the request during a breakfast meeting with 
high-ranking officials at the Ministry of International Trade 
and Industry (MITI), including Eijiro Hata, the trade minister. 
  The fiscal 1994 national budget should be enacted at the 
earliest possible time, while tax reform and deregulation 
packages should be worked out by the end of this month, Toyoda 
was quoted as saying by the MITI official. 
  Yutaka Kume, Keidanren's vice chairman, asked for the 
corporate tax burden be eased and a landholding tax to be 
abolished, to spur overall corporate activity in Japan. 
  Kume, chairman of Nissan Motor Co., also proposed the 
government support research activity at universities and 
national institutes as part of efforts to upgrade Japan's 
industrial infrastructure, the MITI official said. 
  Hata replied that the ministry will respond to these 
requests 
"positively," the official said. 
  On the worsening of employment prospects for college 
graduates, Toyoda said Keidenren will urge business corporations 
to step up new recruitment, especially of female graduates, who 
are finding it extremely difficult to get jobs. 

</TEXT>

