<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to DPRK's Reported IAEA Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reaction to DPRK's Reported IAEA Withdrawal </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Officials Comment </H4>

<F P=102> SK1406000994 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 2210 GMT 13 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK1406000994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] As North Korea has suddenly declared its withdrawal 
from the International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA], the 
government is seeking various countermeasures while analyzing 
the details of North Korea's announcement. 
  After North Korea suddenly reported its withdrawal from the 
IAEA yesterday [13 June], government officials at the National 
Unification Board and the Foreign Ministry stayed in their 
offices late at night to grasp the real intention of North Korea 
by communicating with friendly nations, such as the United 
States and Japan. They also came to their offices earlier than 
usual this morning and are trying to seek measures, anticipating 
North Korea's countermeasure against possible sanctions by the 
UN Security Council. 
  Regarding North Korea's declaration of its withdrawal from 
the IAEA, a government official said: North Korea's action is 
analyzed to have double purpose, to express its dissatisfaction 
at the recent adoption of the IAEA resolution on sanctions 
against it and to convey its strong message against the future 
sanctions by the UN Security Council. 
  He continued: The government will strongly cope with North 
Korea's threatening offensive, acting in concert with the 
international community's effort to guarantee North Korea's 
nuclear transparency. 
  Another government official said: Even after it declared 
that it was withdrawing from the IAEA, North Korea did not 
mention that it would not allow nuclear inspections at all, but 
said that it would not allow inspections for a limited time 
until it decides whether to withdraw from the Nuclear 
Nonproliferation Treaty [NPT]. This hints at North Korea's will 
to completely withdraw from the NPT system if the UN Security 
Council makes a decision to impose sanctions against it. 
  He then anticipated that such an action by North Korea, 
however, would not block the international community's process 
to push for sanctions by the UN Security Council. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

