<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to DPRK's Reported IAEA Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reaction to DPRK's Reported IAEA Withdrawal </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    `Multifaceted Measures' Prepared </H4>

<F P=102> SK1406001994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0010 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1406001994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 14 (YONHAP) -- The government has 
decided to prepare multifaceted measures in response to North 
Korea's reported withdrawal from the International Atomic Energy 
Agency (IAEA). 
  In this connection, the government will make an official 
announcement on the issue Tuesday morning after convening a 
committee to coordinate national unification and security 
policy. The meeting is chaired by Deputy Prime Minister Yi 
Hong-ku, who is also national unification minister. 
  The government will likely urge North Korea to rejoin the 
IAEA and support international efforts to halt nuclear 
proliferation, in the judgement that Pyongyang's withdrawal from 
the agency is a direct refusal of international demands for 
nuclear transparency. 
  A government official said Pyongyang's announcement of its 
withdrawal from the IAEA could not be justified for any reason, 
stressing that "North Korea could not avoid the corresponding 
disadvantage unless it would abide by its duties as a member of 
the international community." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

