<H3> <TI>   Minister Urges Safeguards </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister Urges Safeguards </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1406014194 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0100 GMT 14 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK1406014194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] After attending a Unification and Security Policy 
Coordination Council meeting this morning, Yi Hong-ku, deputy 
prime minister and minister of the National Unification Board, 
said that North Korea's attempt [as heard] to withdraw from the 
International Atomic Energy Agency runs counter to a peaceful 
solution to the nuclear problem. He also urged North Korea to 
implement all nuclear safeguards measures, though belatedly. 
You will listen to it directly from him. 
  [Begin Yi Hong-ku recording] I cannot but clearly point out 
that North Korea's withdrawing from the mechanism of all 
safeguards measures for ensuring the denuclearization of the 
Korean peninsula would decisively run counter to a peaceful 
solution to the nuclear problem [pihaekhwarul pojanghanun modun 
anjonjochiui tureso pukhani ital handanun kosun haengmunjeui 
pyongjok haegyore kyolchongjoguro yokhaeng handanun kosul 
myongbaekhui chijokhaji anulsu opsumnida]. 
  Therefore, I strongly urge North Korea to cooperate, though 
belatedly [chigum irado], with regard to all safeguards measures 
required by the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

