<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Warns About Expulsion </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Warns About Expulsion </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1406085794 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0800 GMT 14 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK1406085794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] It is predicted that the situation will develop 
into a grave phase if North Korea, which has declared its 
withdrawal from the International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA], 
should go out of the way to expel two IAEA inspectors who are 
now staying in North Korea. 
  A government official concerned warned: As a sovereign 
state, North Korea has the full freedom to withdraw from an 
international organization. If North Korea should expel the 
IAEA inspectors who are now staying in Pyongyang, however, this 
will not only be noncompliance with Nuclear Nonproliferation 
Treaty [NPT], but also a direct challenge to the UN Security 
Council (?exhorting) that inspectors be permanently stationed in 
Pyongyang. This will bring about a serious consequence. 
  He also said: North Korea's duty to undergo IAEA nuclear 
inspections is not a requirement as a member of the IAEA, but as 
a party concerned to the NPT. Therefore, North Korea's latest 
measure is evaluated to be nothing but a political message 
simply aimed at achieving symbolic effects. 

</TEXT>

