<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Kim: Not Surprising </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Kim: Not Surprising </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1406101894 Seoul YONHAP in English 1012 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1406101894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 14 (YONHAP) -- President Kim Yong-sam 
said on Tuesday North Korea's withdrawal from the International 
Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) was not anything surprising but was 
anticipated when the IAEA adopted sanctions against them 
recently. 
  "The withdrawal appears to be the initiative taken to avoid 
the disgrace of their being kicked out of the atomic energy 
agency," the president said. 
  While meeting with a group of 15 Mindan (pro-Seoul Korean 
Residents Association in Japan) leaders at Chongwadae 
[presidential offices], President Kim said that thus far there 
had been no signs of unusual military movement in North Korea. 
  He said Pyongyang's withdrawal from the IAEA seems directed 
against South Korea and the United States -- the United States 
in particular. 
  The president noted that the withdrawal was announced at 11 
p.m. Korea time Monday, which was a morning hour in the east of 
the United States. 
  Later in the day, President Kim met leading American 
businessmen who were in Seoul attending the seventh Korea-U.S. 
business conference. 
  Kim called on the visitors to invest more in Korea, saying 
there would be no problem in investment in Korea thanks to 
durable peace brought about by a firm cooperative system between 
South Korea and the United States. 
  The government would ease investment conditions and 
deregulate control so that foreign businesses would find it 
easier to do business in Korea, the president was quoted as 
saying by Chongwadae spokesman Chu Ton-sik. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

