<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   MAC, Defense Ministry Suspend Panmunjom Tours </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    MAC, Defense Ministry Suspend Panmunjom Tours </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1406024394 Seoul YONHAP in English 0235 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1406024394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 14 (YONHAP) -- The Military Armistice 
Commission (MAC) has suspended foreign tourist trips to the 
truce village of Panmunjom, while the South Korean Defense 
Ministry is restricting the number of foreigners who visit 
underground tunnels near the truce line, tourism sources said 
Tuesday. 
  The moves are apparently related to the rising tension 
fueled 
by the North Korean nuclear dispute, the sources said. 
  The MAC recently notified the Korea Travel Bureau, Inc. of 
its decision to suspend visits by foreign tourists to Panmunjom 
for a week from Monday. The travel company has exclusive rights 
to arrange foreign tourists' trips to Panmunjom. 
  Without citing any reason, the MAC said that such tours 
would 
be possible again in a week. 
  With the MAC notification, the travel company has canceled 
Panmumjom tours which amount to an average 100 foreign tourists 
per day. 
  A business source said the MAC has often suspended Panmunjom 
tours according to conditions at the truce village, such as 
military training, and speculated that the abrupt suspension 
might not be related to the tension between South and North 
Korea. 
  Meanwhile, the Defense Ministry recently did not approve 
parts of applications submitted by travel agencies for 
foreigners to tour underground tunnels dug by North Korea at the 
truce line, causing the cancellation of these tours. 
  Another business source said the Defense Ministry had 
notified the Korea Association of General Travel Agents that the 
number of Korean and foreign tourists recently exceeded the 
appropriate number of people to observe the tunnels. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

