<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jiang Zemin's Interview on Nuclear Issue Cited </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Jiang Zemin's Interview on Nuclear Issue Cited </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1106052094 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0450 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1106052094 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Chinese President Jiang Zemin Says China Is Not in Favor </F>
of Imposing Sanctions"--KCNA headline] 
  [Text] Pyongyang, June 11 (KCNA) -- Jiang Zemin, general 
secretary of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of 
China and president of the People's Republic of China, clarified 
China's stand regarding the nuclear issue on the Korean 
peninsula in his interview with a chief commentator of the Japan 
Broadcasting Corporation in Zhongnanhai on June 10. 
  He said: 
  "China is not in favor of imposing sanctions because that is 
useless for the settlement of the problem. On the contrary, it 
would aggravate the escalation of the situation and lead to a 
serious consequence that all parties concerned do not want to 
see. 
  "It is my view that persevering in dialogue and 
consultations 
is an effective and fundamental way to solve the problem". 
  "We urge all parties concerned to exercise restraint and act 
with caution," he said, and added: "The goal for the settlement 
of the issue is finally to safeguard peace and stability on the 
Korean peninsula and realize denuclearization. 
  "No matter what temporary difficulties may appear, it is 
possible to find a proper solution to this problem as long as 
these two major objectives are not departed from." 
  Noting that the door for negotiation is not completely 
closed 
and that there still exist possibilities of holding dialogue, he 
urged all parties concerned to take positive measures so as to 
avoid acceleration of the crisis. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

