<F P=100> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Discusses Current Situation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister Discusses Current Situation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1106131794 Phnom Penh AKP in French 0413 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK1106131794 </F>
<F P=104>  Phnom Penh AKP </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Phnom Penh 11 Jun (AKP) -- Prince Norodom Sirivut, 
deputy prime minister and minister of foreign affairs and 
international cooperation of the Kingdom of Cambodia, returned 
to Phnom Penh on 9 June after a month-long tour, from May 7th 
onward, of France and EC countries. 
  On his return to Phnom Penh he said that "foreign military 
aid to the government army to fight Khmer Rouge rebels will 
bring stability but will not affect the peace process in the 
country." 
  In the meantime, Prince Norodom Sirivut attended the 11th 
conference of nonaligned countries, held from 31 May to 3 June, 
in Cairo (Egypt). During his stay in France he specified that 
he had asked for French aid for the Cambodian Army. "When we 
asked for military assistance, it was not that we wanted to 
aggravate the situation; we want stability," added Prince 
Norodom Sirivut. 
  Australia, France, and the United States are discussing the 
request to train and equip some 160,000 government combatants. 
The Khmer Rouge have vigorously condemned all foreign aid. 
  Prince Norodom Sirivut reaffirmed that the royal government 
does not however want to continue the war against the rebels. 
According to him, the government and Cambodia's king, His 
Majesty Norodom Sihanouk, are trying to bring the guerrillas 
into the national community. 
  Cambodia's chief diplomat also pointed out that he has 
received a 10-point proposal from the Thai Army aimed at 
settling border problems between the two countries. 
  "I am very happy to hear about this proposal from the Thai 
Army; it is a good proposal; I appreciate it," said the prince 
without giving further details. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-28896 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas114_j_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-114 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Indonesia </F>
<H3> <TI>   3-Day Air Defence Exercise Finishes 10 Jun </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    3-Day Air Defence Exercise Finishes 10 Jun </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1306163194 Jakarta ANTARA in English 1451 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK1306163194 </F>
<F P=104>  Jakarta ANTARA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Jakarta, Jun 13 (ANTARA) -- The three-day air 
defence exercise dubbed "Cakra A/94" involving F-5E Tiger II and 
A-4 Sky Hawk tactical jet aircraft, wound up in Jakarta Friday 
last week. 
  National Air Defence Command (Kohanudnas) spokesman 
Lieutenant Colonel Widoso Sabarno said in Jakarta Monday that 
the exercise took place in the air territory under the Air 
Defence Sector Command I [Roman numeral one] covering Jakarta 
and its surroundings. 
  Also taking part in the event, he added, were a number of 
C-130 Hercules giant transport planes and Boeing 707 aircraft, 
in addition to radar units, with Flight Lieutenant Colonel Tahir 
Harita in charge of control and supervision. 
  Widoso said the main purpose of the exercise was to enhance 
the combat readiness of the air defence potential of the 
particular region. 
  The ability and preparedness in the detection, control, and 
interception of enemy aircraft under the air defence operation 
procedures and control command mechanism, have really been 
tested during the exercise, he said. 
  The exercise was also to train combat pilots in quick 
reaction, target identification, action against a target 
including cashing [as received] away, forcing to land up to 
shooting down, Widoso said. 
  In the exercise, the A-4 Sky Hawks acted as the enemy, 
flying 
from their base in Pekanbaru, Riau, for penetration to Jakarta. 
  The A-4 jets were detected by ground radar, then `met' by 
the 
F-5 combat planes, and eventually chased away. 
  The exercise was officially closed by Kohanudnas Commander 
Rear Marshal Sujitno. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-28897 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas114_k_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-114 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Laos </F>
<H3> <TI>   SLORC Chairman Than Shwe Ends Official Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SLORC Chairman Than Shwe Ends Official Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Visit Said `Glorious Success' </H4>

<F P=102> BK1306144394 Vientiane Vitthayou Hengsat Radio Network in 
Lao 1200 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1306144394 </F>
<F P=104>  Vientiane Vitthayou Hengsat Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Lao </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] After ending with glorious success a five-day 
official friendship visit to the Lao People's Democratic 
Republic [LPDR], His Excellency [H.E.] Than Shwe, chairman of 
the State Law and Order Restoration Council [SLORC] of the Union 
of Myanmar [Burma], his wife, and a high-level delegation of the 
Union of Myanmar left Vientiane for home this morning. A 
ceremony to bid farewell to H.E. Than Shwe, his wife, and 
delegation was held at the Hokham Presidential Office in 
Vientiane at 0740. Attending the ceremony were H.E. Nouhak 
Phoumsavan, president of the LPDR, and his wife; H.E. Khamphoui 
Keoboualapha, deputy prime minister and chairman of the Planning 
and Cooperation Committee; H.E. Somsavat Lengsavat, minister of 
foreign affairs; H.E. Choummali Sai-gnason, minister of national 
defense; H.E. Sisavat Keobounphan, minister of agriculture and 
forestry; and H.E. Thongdam Chanthaphon, minister and chief of 
the Presidential Office; along with ministers, deputy ministers, 
and many high-ranking cadres. Also on hand to see the Myanmar 
delegation off at the airport was H.E. Kideng Thammavong, 
ambassador of the LPDR to the Union of Myanmar. 
  During the five-day visit to Laos, H.E. Than Shwe and his 
delegation called on and held talks with H.E. Nouhak Phoumsavan, 
president of the LPDR, and delegation. They also paid a 
courtesy call on H.E. Khamtai Siphandon, chairman of the Lao 
People's Revolutionary Party Central Committee and prime 
minister of the LPDR. Following the meeting and talks, three 
cooperation agreements were jointly signed. In addition, the 
high-level delegation of the Union of Myanmar visited several 
cultural and production establishments in Vientiane and Luang 
Prabang Provinces. It also viewed and paid respects to the That 
Louang Pagoda, Sisaket, and Phakeo Temples in Vientiane. The 
Myanmar delegation also visited the friendship bridge across the 
Mekong River and the Multiethnic Cultural Park in Vientiane 
Municipality. 
  At the farewell ceremony at the Hokham Presidential Office, 
H.E. Than Shwe expressed thanks to H.E. Nouhak Phoumsavan, wife, 
and delegation for the warm welcome accorded him and his 
delegation in an atmosphere of fraternal and neighborly 
friendship and profound mutual understanding. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

