<H3> <TI>   Hata, Clinton Discuss DPRK Issue on Phone </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata, Clinton Discuss DPRK Issue on Phone </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Phone Conversation Held </H4>

<F P=102> OW1406053494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0509 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1406053494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 14 KYODO -- Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata 
and U.S. President Bill Clinton discussed over the phone Tuesday 
North Korea's reported decision to pull out from the United 
Nations' nuclear watchdog, Japanese officials said. 
  The conversation, which lasted about 18 minutes, followed 
Pyongyang's announcement Monday that it has decided to withdraw 
from the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) due to 
"unreasonable sanctions" imposed by the agency. 
  The punitive action was taken for North Korea's rejection of 
inspections of its nuclear facilities suspected of being used 
for nuclear arms development. 
  The Vienna-based IAEA says it has not received any word from 
Pyongyang about the reported move. 

</TEXT>

