<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-114 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to DPRK's Reported IAEA Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reaction to DPRK's Reported IAEA Withdrawal </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    No `Written Notification' </H4>

<F P=102> SK1406011494 Seoul YONHAP in English 0107 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1406011494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Berlin, June 14 (YONHAP) -- North Korea, which 
announced it would quit the International Atomic Energy Agency 
(IAEA) on Monday, has yet to officially notify the agency of the 
decision, IAEA officials said. 
  In addition, Pyongyang has not sent written notification to 
the United States, the depository country for the IAEA 
statitutes. 
  North Korea's withdrawal does not take effect according to 
international law unless the country sends written notification 
to the United States and then the IAEA Secretariat gives an 
authoritative interpretation to effect this notification. 
  But since North Korea's nuclear safeguards agreement holds 
unless it leaves the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty (NPT), its 
announced withdrawal from the IAEA carries symbolic meaning of 
defying the IAEA sanctions resolution rather than any practical 
significance. 
  The IAEA Board of Governors passed a sanctions resolution 
against North Korea on Friday with overwhelming support. The 
resolution provides for an immediate halt to IAEA technical 
assistance totaling 500,000-600,000 dollars a year to Pyongyang. 
  The agency is studying North Korea's reason for announcing 
its withdrawal and will monitor the stalinist state's follow-up 
steps. 
  The North has apparently not restricted the activities of 
the 
IAEA inspection team currently in Yongbyon, but is likely to act 
soon after announcing it can no longer guarantee the continuity 
of nuclear safeguards, according to IAEA officials. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

