<H3> <TI>   Daily Views Failure of Trade Talks with U.S. </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Daily Views Failure of Trade Talks with U.S. </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1506082794 Jakarta Radio Republik Indonesia Network in 
Indonesian 0600 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1506082794 </F>
<F P=104>  Jakarta Radio Republik Indonesia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Indonesian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the press review] </F>
  [Text] KOMPAS discusses the failure of the textile trade 
talks between Indonesia and the United States in Bali last 
weekend. The earlier talks, held in Washington, also failed to 
reach an agreement. Therefore, it was the second time the talks 
were not successful. 
  The United States continues to reject Indonesia's request to 
increase the export quota of Indonesian textiles and textile 
products by 14 percent for certain textile categories. The 
United States is willing to increase the quota by 2 percent, and 
Indonesia cannot accept that. 
  As for the U.S. demand to have access to Indonesian markets 
for its commodity goods, a concrete agreement has not been 
reached yet. Against this background, KOMPAS urges the 
Indonesian Government to approach not only the USTR in 
Washington, but also the U.S. Senate, the State Department, the 
Agriculture Department, the U.S. Customs, and American business 
circles. As such, the success of the talks will be determined 
not only in formal negotiations but also through informal 
relations and personal approach. Such a personal approach is 
needed in future talks to produce results desired by Indonesia. 

</TEXT>

