<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Voice of America Cited on U.S. Sanctions Plans </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Voice of America Cited on U.S. Sanctions Plans </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1106105694 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1034 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1106105694 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["The United States Does Not Know How Bold and Decisive </F>
Supreme Commander Kim Chong-il Is; Radio Voice of America" -- 
KCNA headline] 
  [Text] Pyongyang, June 11 (KCNA) -- Radio Voice of America 
said on June 5 that there is a heated discussion on what phase 
would be created by "sanctions" against North Korea in the U.S. 
Congress, academic and public circles and even in the U.S. 
military. 
  The radio said that the dove camp, especially former U.S. 
high-ranking officials and former U.S. generals who were 
involved in the policy toward North Korea for a rather long 
period and who, staying in South Korea, frequently contacted 
North Korea repeatedly advised Washington to ponder over the 
matter, saying it is a mistake if it thought "sanctions" or 
"military response" against North Korea would be effective. 
  The radio quoted them as saying the United States does not 
know North Korea yet and, particularly, how bold and decisive 
supreme commander Kim Chong-il is. Suffice it to recall the 
situation on the Korean peninsula which abruptly took a critical 
turn in March last year, they said. 
  The radio quoted them as stressing that the U.S. must know 
well the preparedness of the North Korean Army equipped with 
modern weapons and well trained for action. 
  Not a few figures in the United States hold that, no matter 
how important the "nuclear issue" may be, the United States must 
open the door for dialogue to North Korea once again before 
taking "sanctions" and "military countermeasure", the radio said. 

</TEXT>

