<H3> <TI>   Foreign Media Reportedly Criticize U.S. Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Media Reportedly Criticize U.S. Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1106104594 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1014 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1106104594 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["U.S. Hostile Policy Toward Korea Will Fail" -- KCNA </F>
headline] 
  [Text] Pyongyang, June 11 (KCNA) -- World public bitterly 
condemned the anti-DPRK nuclear racket of the United States and 
its followers. 
  The Malian paper AURORE May 19 said that since the DPRK-U.S. 
talks for a solution to the nuclear issue of the Korean 
peninsula broke up, the situation in the peninsula has become 
extremely acute. It charged that Washington and Seoul were 
stepping up nuclear war preparations, crying for "sanctions" 
against North Korea. 
  The nuclear issue on the Korean peninsula, it noted, can be 
resolved only through negotiations between the DPRK and the U.S. 
  A radio of Iran May 31 said the United States is claiming 
pressure and "sanctions" against the Democratic People's 
Republic of Korea only, while failing to throw into question 
Israel that has many nuclear weapons. 
  The U.S. hostile policy vis-a-vis Korea will fail in face of 
the resistance from the world people, it said. 
  The May issue of the Dutch magazine INTERNATIONAL LIBERATION 
said the question of guaranteeing peace on the Korean peninsula 
in the future depends on the U.S. attitude. 
  Noting that the U.S. troops stationed in South Korea are 
equipped with nuclear weapons and extensively staging war 
exercises against the DPRK, the magazine said the DPRK has its 
independent right to protect itself from a U.S. nuclear attack. 

</TEXT>

