<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Christian Groups Reported To Object to Sanctions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Christian Groups Reported To Object to Sanctions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1306102394 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1001 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1306102394 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, June 13 (KCNA) -- The National Council of 
Christian Churches of South Korea in a policy discussion of the 
reunification committee June 10 said that the U.S.-led move of 
"sanctions" against the North might get on its nerve and 
demanded that "the United States stop utterances and acts 
creating tensions on the Korean peninsula," a Seoul-based radio 
said. 
  Noting that the authorities' inconsistent "policy" towards 
the North increases the confusion and uneasiness of the people, 
the organisation decided to strongly urge the puppet authorities 
to "shape and promote a reunification policy giving top priority 
to the existence and peace of the nation." 
  The Federation of Christian Social Movement in a recent 
statement clarified its stand opposed to "`sanctions' against 
the North," that heightens the war crisis. 

</TEXT>

