<F P=100> INTER-ASIAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Malaysian Minister Speaks at Straits Conference </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Malaysian Minister Speaks at Straits Conference </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1406100794 Kuala Lumpur Voice of Malaysia in English 0800 
GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1406100794 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur Voice of Malaysia </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Malaysia has reiterated the need for appropriate and 
acceptable mechanisms to relieve coastal states of the onerous 
responsibility and burden of keeping the Straits of Malacca safe. 
  Foreign Minister Datuk Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said it is 
patently unfair to expect the littoral states to use national 
funds to underwrite what is, by and large, an international 
responsibility. He adds, however, that the littoral states, 
Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore, and Thailand do not wish to 
adopt any unilateral decision regarding the management of the 
strait, one of the busiest waterways in the world. 
  He was delivering a keynote address at an international 
conference on the Straits of Malacca organized by the Malaysian 
Institute of Maritime Affairs in Kuala Lumpur. The two-day 
inaugural conference attended by about 180 participants will 
discuss matters pertaining to the (?risk) management, 
navigational, and environmental problems of the strait. 
  Datuk Abdullah said there was a need for cooperation to 
secure a safer navigation and a cleaner strait regime because 
many of the potential risks and problems associated with the 
strait were the results of externalities. The problems are 
created by ships in transit as well as multiple use of the 
waterway. He pointed out that the three states are facing the 
situation where the international shipping community use the 
strait on a free of charge basis while the littoral states have 
to bear the financial burden to keep the strait clean and safe. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

