<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK Pushing for UN Resolution in 2-3 Weeks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ROK Pushing for UN Resolution in 2-3 Weeks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1506072094 Seoul YONHAP in English 0711 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1506072094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 15 (YONHAP) -- Foreign Minister Han 
Sung-chu said Wednesday that moves are afoot at the U.N. 
Security Council to complete a draft resolution on North Korea 
this week for adoption in two to three weeks' time. 
  Han made the remark at a meeting of lawmakers and local 
chapter heads from the ruling Democratic Liberal Party held at 
the Lawmakers Hall of the National Assembly. 
  The foreign minister's remarks are understood to signify 
that 
Pyongyang's withdrawal from the International Atomic Energy 
Agency [IAEA] would cause the U.N. resolution to be advanced by 
one week from the original schedule. 
  With regard to China's position on sanctions against 
Pyongyang, Han said, "Intensive diplomatic efforts to win the 
constructive cooperation of China are underway. China is well 
aware that North Korea is accountable for the current critical 
situation of its nuclear row. 
  "Pyongyang's quitting the IAEA will not affect the status of 
the Nuclear Non-proliferation Treaty (NPT). Therefore, as long 
as North Korea does not quit the NPT, the nuclear safeguards 
accord and inspection obligations with the IAEA remain 
effective," he emphasized. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

