<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Premier: No Sign of `Provocation' by DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Premier: No Sign of `Provocation' by DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1506115594 Seoul YONHAP in English 1033 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1506115594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 15 (YONHAP) -- Prime Minister Yi 
Yong-tok said on Wednesday he is positive North Korea will not 
dare to provoke a war against the South. 
  "Preparedness and morale on the part of our Armed Forces are 
higher than any other time in the past, who have the ability to 
crush any North Korean provocation," Yi said. 
  In an interview with the three major televisions in Seoul, 
the premier said that at the moment there is no sign of 
provocation or any unusual military movement in North Korea. 
The prime minister said the fire power of the South Korean and 
U.S. Forces are enormous and the two countries maintain a close 
cooperative system. 
  "Today's civil defense drill was to check our security 
preparedness but the drill was not due to any growing danger of 
war," he said. The premier observed that North Korea seems 
trying to apply some shock therapies like the withdrawal from 
the International Atomic Energy Agency. "But, the strategy does 
not go the way they wish," he added. 

</TEXT>

