<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Shifts Into `Top Gear' for Intelligence </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Shifts Into `Top Gear' for Intelligence </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1506032394 Seoul YONHAP in English 0316 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1506032394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 15 (YONHAP) -- South Korea and the 
United States have shifted into top gear to conduct joint 
intelligence surveillance of North Korean military activities, 
sources at the Defense Ministry said Wednesday. 
  The allied forces took the action after determining that the 
chances of an unexpected military provocation by North Korea are 
high following its withdrawal from the International Atomic 
Energy Agency, the sources said. 
  The United States is expected to increase the intensity of a 
draft resolution on U.N. sanctions against North Korea. 
Pyongyang has said it would regard the imposition of sanctions 
as an act of war. 
  Defense Minister Yi Pyong-tae said last week that South 
Korean and U.S. military forces have completed preparations for 
three possible stages -- the beginning of sanctions, limited 
North Korean provocations and an all-out war. 
  The intelligence surveillance operation would go into full 
operation if and when sanctions were imposed, Yi said. 
  At present, the United States and South Korea have deployed 
U-2R reconnaissance aircraft, E-3C early warning planes, KH-9 
spy satellites and all other possible means to monitor North 
Korean movements around the clock while thoroughly analyzing the 
pictures and information gathered, the sources said. 
  Washington has already sent military analysts and 
intelligence officials to South Korea to support the operation, 
they added. 
  The South Korean military, meanwhile, is rechecking its 
decision- making system in order to meet possible limited 
provocations by North Korea, and strengthening the defense of 
public and government buildings and facilities and military 
command posts that could be targeted in a North Korean attack, 
they said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

