<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Official Claims U.S. Once Agreed to Pullout </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK Official Claims U.S. Once Agreed to Pullout </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1506114694 Seoul YONHAP in English 1123 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1506114694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris, June 15 (YONHAP) -- The United States had 
accepted the principle of U.S. military withdrawal from South 
Korea in a "secret agreement" signed with North Korea last 
February, the French daily LIBERATION quoting a senior North 
Korean official here reported Wednesday. 
  The report said that the official, Pak Tong-chun, head of 
the 
North Korean mission in Paris, claimed that Washington accepted 
the principle of pulling 37,000 American troops out of South 
Korea under the frame of a "secret" bilateral agreement which 
was agreed in December 1993 in New York and concluded last 
February. 
  "The United States asked us not to leak this, but they 
breached all the promises later," Pak was quoted as saying. 
  The daily said Pak failed to produce any evidence and a 
spokesman for the U.S. State Department declined a comment on 
Pak's allegation. 
  Meanwhile, in an interview with the INTERNATIONAL HERALD 
TRIBUNE, Pak denied North Korea's nuclear development but said 
his country is prepared to wage a war if it is necessary to 
safeguard "our essential national interests." He said that any 
North Korean attack on the United States, China or Japan with 
nuclear weapons would be a suicidal act. "We cannot even think 
of attacking South Korea, our same people," Pak told the TRIBUNE. 
  Asserting that the United States had invented all problems 
like the theory of North Korean attack simply to justify their 
presence in South Korea, Pak said that North Korea has reached 
the limit of patience and has no intent of making concessions 
any further. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

