<H3> <TI>   Former U.S. President Carter Visits ROK, DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Former U.S. President Carter Visits ROK, DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Reportedly Carrying Package Deal Offer </H4>

<F P=102> SK1506004994 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0000 GMT 15 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK1506004994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Correspondent Yi Chong-su's report from Washington] </F>
  [Text] It has been learned that former U.S. President 
Carter, who will visit North Korea today, has a nonofficial 
package offer to solve the North Korean nuclear issue and 
U.S.-North Korean relations simultaneously. 
  In an interview with the Korean Broadcasting System, KBS, 
today a U.S. scholar, who has reportedly played a 
behind-the-scenes role for former U.S. President Carter's visit 
to North Korea, revealed that former President Carter's 
nonofficial package offer contains the improvement of U.S.-North 
Korean relations and the measures for guaranteeing the overall 
security of the Korean peninsula in return for guaranteeing 
North Korea's nuclear transparency. 
  This scholar, who did not want to be identified, said that 
if 
former President Carter achieved no success in his visit to 
North Korea this time, public opinion in the United States would 
quickly turn toward imposing sanctions against North Korea 
within or without the framework of the United Nations. 

</TEXT>

