<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chongwadae `Closely Watching' Carter's Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chongwadae `Closely Watching' Carter's Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1506054494 Seoul YONHAP in English 0535 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1506054494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 15 (YONHAP) -- Chongwadae [presidential 
offices] is closely watching Jimmy Carter's visit to North 
Korea, concerned that Pyongyang may utilize the former U.S. 
President's meeting with strongman Kim Il-song for propaganda 
purposes both at home and abroad as well as for a political 
compromise. 
  A knowledgeable source said Wednesday that if Carter is 
greeted by North Korean Vice Foreign Minister Song Ho-kyong at 
Panmunjom, it might be a North Korean tactic to turn his visit 
into a political negotiation between Washington and Pyongyang. 
The source pointed out that "We have to watch with concern how 
the high-ranking official greets him at Panmunjom." 
  He said, "North Korea has made it a rule to greet former 
heads of state through the chairman or staff of the Committee 
for Cultural Relations With Foreign Countries." He speculated 
that having a Foreign Ministry official meet Carter at Panmunjom 
would signal political negotiation rather than a cordial 
reception. 
  As to reports that Chinese President Jiang Zemin refused to 
discuss the North Korean nuclear problem with President Clinton 
over the phone, he explained, "China seems discontent that 
Pyongyang has not consulted beforehand with it on the 
announcement to quit the International Atomic Energy Agency." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

