<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Begins Monitoring Prices of Basic Goods </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Begins Monitoring Prices of Basic Goods </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1506014594 Seoul YONHAP in English 0133 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1506014594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 15 (YONHAP) -- The government, expecting 
that the tension over North Korea's withdrawal from the 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) will drag on, has 
begun monitoring the prices of basic consumer goods such as 
rice, ramyon (instant noodles) and jewelry, as well as the stock 
market, every day. No hoarding of daily necessities has yet 
been observed, but the supply shortages and resulting runaway 
inflation expected from a steep escalation in tension would 
throw the economy into confusion, officials said Wednesday. To 
prepare for an emergency, the government has started checking 
fluctuations of consumer prices and the supply and demand of key 
consumer goods on a daily basis, they added. 
  The Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries is 
monitoring the prices of rice and other farm products, the 
Ministry of Finance and the Bank of Korea movements in the 
financial markets such as interest rates, withdrawals, share 
prices and foreign investment, the ministry of trade, industry 
and energy the prices of manufactured goods, and the Ministry of 
Transportation foreign tourist arrivals. 
  No unusual price movements for such items as rice and ham 
have been detected, the Economic Planning Board said. 
  The government has started daily price checks in preparation 
for unexpected developments after North Korea bolted from the 
IAEA, but nothing unusual has been observed so far, a board 
official said. 
  The government's daily checks come as tensions are expected 
to rise in the wake of North Korea's abrupt withdrawal, he 
added. In case the situation worsens and the economy weakens, 
the government will set in motion an emergency system. 
  Purchases of food, fuel, first-aid drugs, flashlights and 
candles for emergencies are increasing and some prices are on 
the rise. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

